Option 2 is &quot;definitely&quot; best.  But you&#39;ll also want to override toString()
-- otherwise you&#39;ll still get the same incomprehensible error message when
the assert does fail.  

Also, as a safety precaution, you should be in the habit of always
overriding hashCode() any time you override equals().  If not, your object
will be unsafe to store in many collections, and you should at least
document that fact.  But it&#39;s usually very easy--your hashCode() only needs
to ensure that two objects which are equal always have the same hash code.
Following Erik&#39;s example:

    public boolean equals(Object object) {
       if (object instanceof View) {
           return ((View)object).stringToTest.equals(this.stringToTest);
       }
       return false;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return &quot;[View: &quot; + stringToTest + &quot;]&quot;;
    }

    public long hashCode() {
        return stringToTest.hashCode();
    }

I know it seems like a pain, but I got in the habit of adding this trio to
every &quot;Value object&quot; I create and it&#39;s averted many potentially confounding
bugs.

Kevin


